{{Notability|date=September 2009}} '''CoSMoS''' was a UK funded research project seeking to build capacity in generic modelling tools and simulation techniques for complex systems. Its acronym stands for Complex Systems Modelling and Simulation. This was a four-year project, running from 2007 to 2011 as a collaboration between the [[University of York]] and [[University of Kent|Kent]], with further collaborations from the [[University of Abertay Dundee]] and [[Bristol Robotics Laboratory]].
== History == Collaboration between the universities of York and Kent started with the [http://www.cs.york.ac.uk/nature/tuna TUNA project], a feasibility study looking at the requirements for developing networks of [[nanite]]s that behave safely.<ref>{{cite web| title = TUNA - Theory Underpinning Nanotech Assemblers| url = http://www.cs.york.ac.uk/nature/tuna/| accessdate = 20 October 2009}}</ref> This project involved researchers from York, Kent and Surrey. TUNA's outcomes were both conceptual and practical. An example of theoretical contribution consists of investigators showing that [[Emergence|emergent properties]] do not [[Refinement (computing)|refine]] ,<ref>{{cite conference | first = Fiona | last = Polack | authorlink = | author2 = Stepney, S. | title = Emergent properties do not refine | booktitle = REFINE 2005 workshop | pages = 163–181 | date = July 2005 | publisher = Elsevier | location = Guildford | volume = 137 | number = 2 | series = ENTSC | url = http://www-users.cs.york.ac.uk/~fiona/PUBS/REFINE05.pdf | accessdate = 20 October 2009}}</ref> but gave insights into the engineering of emergence.<ref>{{cite conference | first = Susan | last = Stepney | authorlink = | author2 = Polack, F.| author3 = Turner, H. | title = Engineering emergence | booktitle = Proceedings of the 11th IEEE International Conference on Engineering of Complex Computer Systems | pages = 89–97 | year = 2006 | publisher = IEEE Computer Society | url = http://www.cs.york.ac.uk/nature/tuna/outputs/Stepney-iceccs06.pdf | accessdate = 20 October 2009}}</ref> Practical results were obtained through the use of a blood clotting case-study. This led to the development of a [[Process-oriented programming|process-oriented]], large-scale simulation <ref>{{cite web| title = 3D Blood Clotting| url = https://www.cs.kent.ac.uk/research/groups/plas/wiki/3D_Blood_Clotting| accessdate = 20 October 2009}}</ref> implemented in [[occam-pi]].
